    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-02T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-02T10:00:00-05:00" n="360"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.6174/11: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Earle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-02T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >December 2, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 3—7:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>466. Russian Minister informs me that the Bulgarian police are doing everything
                    possible to annoy and isolate his Legation. Every member of the Legation is
                    openly followed by police and every visitor except diplomats leaving the
                    Legation is questioned by the police and sometimes arrested. The Russian
                    Counsellor of Legation was recently beaten on the street by plain-clothes men
                    while a uniformed policeman looked on.</p>
                <p>Complaints to the Foreign Minister by the Russian Minister bring no relief.</p>
                <pb facs="0348" n="336" xml:id="pg_336"/>
                <p>It is probable that these tactics are but further evidence of the crude and
                    brutal police system and the lack of control of the Foreign Office over the
                    police. It is possible, however, it is a studied persecution intended to cause
                    Russia to break relations with Bulgaria, though the Russian Minister says this
                    will not happen because of such provocations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Earle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For declaration of war on December 12 and 13, 1941, between the United
                        States and Bulgaria, Rumania, and Hungary, see <ref target="#pg_591">pages
                            591</ref> and <ref target="#pg_592">592</ref>.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
